          "body": "Verses 13-18 are the chapter's anti-sentimental coda. Day Two of the seventh month, the leaders return for deeper study, and they discover within the Law the command to dwell in booths during the seventh month (Leviticus 23:42-43) — a feast the text says had not been properly kept 'from the days of Joshua the son of Nun to that day' (8:17). A thousand-year gap of unobserved obedience is closed in two weeks. They proclaim, gather branches, build booths on rooftops and in courtyards and in public squares — and 'there was great rejoicing' (8:17). The chapter refuses to let comprehension terminate in emotion. What is *found written* (v. 14) must be *done*. The pattern is James 1:22-25 in Old Testament form: the doer of the word, not the hearer only, is blessed in what he does."
