          "title": "The joy of the LORD as covenant strength",
          "body": "The chapter's most quoted verse, 8:10, deserves careful exegesis. 'The joy of the LORD is your strength' — *chedvat YHWH hi maoz-kem*. *Chedvah* is a rare noun for gladness; *maoz* is a fortress or stronghold (the same word used in Psalm 27:1, 'the LORD is the *stronghold* of my life'). The construction is genitive — is it the joy *that the LORD has* (His own delight, communicated to His people) or the joy *that comes from the LORD* (their joy in Him)? Hebrew grammar permits both, and the chapter's context favors holding them together. The God who has given the Book, summoned the assembly, and made the day holy is Himself glad — and His gladness, received by His people, becomes the fortress in which they live covenant life. Joy is not the byproduct of obedience; it is the engine of it. A people without joy in YHWH have no resources for the long obedience the covenant requires."
